I used the results from the Breslow Day test(s) to determine if I should report either the M-H Adjusted OR or the Crude Stratifed OR for each outcome of interest. I recorded the results in a spreadsheet where the variables are divided by different outcomes of interest such as risky behaviors, health outcomes, and environmental factors.

Creating New Data Frames

In the following code, I’ll be extracting the Crude Stratified ORs and the M-H Adjusted ORs from the ‘results’ list from the previous code chunk. I’ll create a data frame for each that’ll allow me to use ggplot2 for visualizations.

#initialize empty data frame
crude_or_data <- data.frame( #creates data frame w/ columns
  Variable = character(), #stores the name if the variable from 'ovars' list and is initlizaed as a character (avoids R from treating as factor/category)
  Strata = character(), #stores the name of the different strata ("White", "Hispanic", etc)
  OR = numeric(),     #stores ORs as numeric vector
  CI_lower = numeric(), 
  CI_upper = numeric(),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE #ensures chr vectors aren't automatically turned to factors 
)

# Loop through 'results' to extract crude stratified ORs
for(i in 1:length(results)) { #loop goes through each item/variable in the 'results' list
  crude_ors <- results[[i]]$`Crude Stratified ORs` #pulls out ORs and their conf. intervals
  strata_names <- rownames(crude_ors)   #pulls the names of the different strata that the ORs are calculated for
  
  for(j in 1:nrow(crude_ors)) {   #loop goes through each group within the current variable and pulls out OR for that group
    crude_or_data <- rbind(crude_or_data, data.frame( #adds a new row to table for each group, rbind allows rws to be added together 
      Variable = names(results)[i], #adds names of current variable (like "QN10")
      Strata = strata_names[j],  #adds name of the group (like "Black/AA")
      OR = crude_ors[j, "est"],  #extract the OR
      CI_lower = crude_ors[j, "lower"],  #lower CI
      CI_upper = crude_ors[j, "upper"]   #upper CI
    ))
  }
}

# View the data frame
print(crude_or_data)

For the outcomes of interest above, I reported the Stratified Crude ORs because the Breslow-Day test revealed significant differences (with p-values < 0.05) in how sexual identity affects the outcome across different racial groups. Reflecting on the Stratified Crude ORs will provide a clear view of how these effects vary between groups. The Mantel-Haenszel adjusted ORs, which give an overall average, might not accurately reflect these variations and could lead to ignoring important differences.

QN10 Interpretation: Black/AA and Hispanic/Latino sexual minority students demonstrate a higher likelihood of drunk driving compared to White heterosexual students. Black/AA sexual minority students show about 2.54 times the odds of drunk driving, and Hispanic/Latino sexual minority students show about 1.64 odds, which is slightly elevated, however not as much as Black/African American students.

QN41 Interpretation: QN41 represents the percentage of students who drank alcohol (at least one drink) on at least one day during the 30 days before the survey. Compared to their White heterosexual counterparts, all three Strata (Black/AA, Hispanic/Latino and Other Racial groups) demonstrate significantly higher odds of drinking.
- Black/AA sexual minority students show about 2.31 higher odds of drinking alcohol compared to White heterosexual students - Hispanic/Latino sexual minority students show about 1.50 higher odds of drinking alcohol compared to White heterosexual students - Other Racial/Ethnic sexual minority groups (including Pacific Islanders and Native Americans) show roughly 1.62 higher odds of drinking compared to White heterosexual students

QN85 Interpretation QN85 regards students who reported that their mental health was not good (including stress, anxiety, and depression) most of the time or always during the 30 days before the survey. For all three strata (Black/AA, Hispanic/Latino, and Other racial/ethnic groups) there is a statistically significant association with reporting poor mental health, as demonstrated by their confidence intervals not crossing 1 (1 represents no difference at all). - Hispanic/Latino sexual minority students

QN97 Interpretation QN97 represents the percentage of students who reported that their parents or other adults in their family most of the time or always know where they are going or with whom they will be. The crude stratified ORs for Black/AA, Hispanic/Latino and other racial/ethnic groups show no strong evidence/statistical significance that these strata differ from White students (since the confidence interval for each includes 1). Plotting Mantel-Haenszel Adjusted Odd Ratios

mhadj_selected <- mhadj_data %>%
  filter(Variable %in% c("QN11", "QN13", "QN28", "QN83", "QN30", "QN59", "QN87", "QN18"))

mhadj_selected %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Variable, y = OR)) +
  geom_point(size = 4, color = "blue") +  
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = CI_lower, ymax = CI_upper), width = 0.5, color = "blue") +  #error bars for CI
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +  #line at OR = 1
  coord_flip() +  #flip coordinates to make horizontal
  labs(x = "Outcome(s) of Interest",
       y = "Mantel-Haenszel Adjusted Odds Ratio (OR)", 
       title = "Mantel-Haenszel Adjusted Odds Ratios with 95% Confidence Intervals") +
  theme_bw() + 
   geom_text(aes(label = round(OR, 2)),  #text labels w/ OR values rounded to 2 decimal places
            vjust = -1, #move text slightly above points
            size = 3, #text/label size
            color = "black")

For the outcomes above, I reported and plotted the Mantel-Haenszel (M-H) Adjusted ORs because the Breslow Day test yielded p-values greater than 0.05 for each, indicating no statistical significance between sexual identity and race/ethnicity on these outcomes.

Reporting the M-H Adjusted ORs provided measures of the overall effect of sexual identity identity on these outcomes while accounting for race/ethnicity. This approach combines data across all ethnic/racial groups and yields a single measure (OR) (with lower and upper bound confidence intervals), giving a clearer picture when the effect doesn’t change significantly between groups.

QN11 Interpretation: The QN11 dichotomous variable in the YRBSS represents those students who reported texting while driving. Given that the OR is less than 1 (0.78), this means that overall our population of interest (sexual minority students of racial/ethnic minority status) has about 22% lower odds of texting while driving compared to the reference group (White heterosexual students).

QN13 Interpretation: QN13 represents those students who reported carrying a gun to school (excluding hunting or sport-related reasons) at least one day in the past 12 months. A M-H adjusted OR of 0.86 indicates that the odds of sexual minority students who’re also of minority race/ethnicity have slightly lower odds of carrying a gun to school as opposed to their White counterparts (about 14%).

QN28 Interpretation: QN28 variable corresponds to the percentage of students who attempted suicide at least once in the past 12 months.
